Project Summary

This case study was completed to fulfill the Capstone Project requirement of the Google Data Analytics Professional Certificate.

Background:

Bellabeat is a wellness company which manufactures a health and fitness tracking app which collects and displays data from several smart devices.

Business Task:

Analyze and leverage trends in consumer usage of smart devices to inform Bellabeat’s marketing strategy.

Data Sources:

Data is not available from Bellabeat devices, so proxy data from the FitBit Fitness Tracker Data dataset is used for this analysis. No metadata is available for the variables included in this dataset.

This dataset consists of thirty-five FitBit users’ sleep, weight, and physical activity data obtained from FitBit devices between March 12th, 2016 and May 12th, 2016.

  • Fitness data includes number of steps, calories burned, heart rate, metabolic equivalent of task (MET), intensity, distance, and time.
  • Weight data includes weight kg/lbs, fat, and BMI.
  • Sleep data includes minutes asleep and time in bed.

For certain variables, data is aggregated differently across different files. This analysis focuses on activity data at the activity-session level (e.g., number of steps/calories burned per activity session) and daily weight and sleep data.

Data Cleaning and Transformation, and Analysis:

Data Cleaning and Validation Checks were performed to identify and correct out-of-range, inconsistent, missing, and duplicated data.

Data Transformation The following key metrics were computed and used in analysis:

  1. Number of participants who used each of the three tracking features (activity, sleep, and weight) each day of data collection.
  2. Average daily percentage of time spent sedentary and engaging in activities at each intensity level.
  3. Median daily minutes asleep, in bed, and awake in bed for each participant.

Additional metrics were computed and documented in the Data Transformation section of this project, but did not reveal insights relevant to the business task.

Summary of Results:

Data Analysis revealed three key actionable insights:

  1. Consumers most frequently used smart devices to track their activity levels. Sleep tracking was the second most frequently used feature. Few consumers used their smart devices to track weight.
  2. Consumers were typically sedentary for about 82% (~17 hours) of the day and engaged in light intensity activity for about 15% (~3 hours) of their day. Consumers only engaged in fairly or very intense activity for about 1-2% of the day, respectively (~14 - 20 minutes).
  3. Consumers typically spent about 6.5 - 8.3 hours asleep each day and spent only a small amount of time in bed when they weren’t sleeping (typically 0 - 45 minutes).

Recommendations:

Bellabeat can leverage these insights to improve their marketing strategy for their Leaf and Time products as follows:

  1. Run ads which market these products as activity tracking devices, but incorporate a social media aspect to the app which allows users to share their activity levels with friends.
  2. Run additional ads which highlight sleep and weight tracking features of the products in key locations such as doctors offices or gyms. Additionally, run these ads online and target them to users with online presence indicating interest in weight loss/gain, insomnia, or sleep hygiene.
  3. Create ads which include content targeted towards highly active people to encourage this demographic to purchase these products.
  4. Create ads which highlight the utility of these products for ensuring a full night of sleep and run them on social media and digital entertainment platforms which consumers are likely to be using when they are in bed before falling asleep.

Full Documentation of Project Code

Data Loading

# Import libraries
library(tidyverse)
library(janitor) # For get_dupes()
library(gridExtra) # For grid.arrange()
# The PieChart function from the lessR package will be used but not loaded
# outright due to conflicts with tidyverse packages
# Read in data
# Specify file paths for each batch of data
path_1 <- './Data_3.12.16-4.11.16'
path_2 <- './Data_4.12.16-5.12.16'

# Combine paths into vector
paths <- c(path_1, path_2)

# Specify file names for each file type
activity_file <- '/dailyActivity_merged.csv'
weight_file <- '/weightLogInfo_merged.csv'
sleep_file <- '/sleepDay_merged.csv'

# Combine file names into vector
files <- c(activity_file, weight_file)

# Read in activity and weight data from each path
for (file in files) {
  # Set data frame name for activity data
  if (file == activity_file) {
    name <- 'activity_data'
  }
  
  # Set data frame name for weight data
  else if (file == weight_file) {
    name <- 'weight_data'
  }
  
  # Read in data as df
  df <- read_csv(c(paste(path_1,
                         file,
                         sep = ""),
                   paste(path_2,
                         file,
                         sep = "")))
  
  # Rename df using predetermined names
  assign(name, df)
  
  # Drop unused df
  rm(df)
}

# Read in sleep data
# Data present from second path only
sleep_data <- read_csv(paste(path_2,
                             sleep_file,
                             sep = ''))

Now, I apply the necessary changes to clean the weight data:

# Convert Date to datetime format and separate, drop duplicates, and arrange by Id and Date
weight_data_clean <- weight_data %>%
  separate_wider_delim(
    Date,
    delim = " ",
    names = c('Date', 'Time'),
    too_many = 'merge'
  ) %>%
  mutate(Date = mdy(Date)) %>%
  mutate(Time = hms(Time)) %>%
  distinct() %>%
  arrange(Id, Date)

Now, apply the necessary corrections to the sleep data:

# Convert SleepDay to date and rename, drop duplicates, compute total awake time
# in bed, and sort sleep data by ID and Date
sleep_data_clean <- sleep_data %>%
  mutate(SleepDay = date(mdy_hms(SleepDay))) %>%
  rename(Date = SleepDay) %>%
  distinct() %>%
  mutate(TotalAwakeTimeInBed = TotalTimeInBed - TotalMinutesAsleep) %>%
  arrange(Id, Date)

Data Transformation

Participants can have more than one recorded activity per day. The following code aggregates activity data by computing daily sums for each activity variable for each participant, then computes total active minutes as the sum of very active, fairly active, lightly active, and sedentary minutes, and finally joins the aggregated daily activity data with daily weight and sleep data.

# Aggregate activity data, compute total active time, compute awake time in bed,
# and merge with other dfs
daily_data <- activity_data_clean %>%
  group_by(Id, Date) %>%
  summarize(across(where(is.numeric), sum)) %>%
  mutate(TotalActiveMinutes =
           VeryActiveMinutes +
           FairlyActiveMinutes +
           LightlyActiveMinutes +
           SedentaryMinutes) %>%
  full_join(weight_data_clean, by = join_by(Id == Id, Date == Date)) %>%
  full_join(sleep_data_clean, by = join_by(Id == Id, Date == Date))

The following code calculates the total number of participants who used each FitBit tracking feature each day and prepares it to graphed.

# Create df of all dates in data set
dates <-
  data.frame('Date' = seq(ymd('2016-03-12'), ymd('2016-05-12'), by = 'days'))

# Create df of all Ids in data set
# Uses activity_data because this df includes the greatest # of participants
ids <- activity_data_clean %>%
  select(Id, Date) %>%
  distinct(Id)

# Create df indicating how many participants used each feature each day
# First create df of all id/date combinations and merge with daily data
# Then create new variables indicating whether each participant used each feature each day
# Then count total number of participants who used each feature each day
# Finally, convert to long format for graphing
feature_usage <- ids %>%
  cross_join(dates) %>%
  full_join(daily_data, by = join_by(Id == Id, Date == Date)) %>%
  mutate(ActivityTracked = ifelse(is.na(TotalSteps) == TRUE, 0, 1)) %>%
  mutate(SleepTracked = ifelse(is.na(TotalMinutesAsleep) == TRUE, 0, 1)) %>%
  mutate(WeightTracked = ifelse(is.na(WeightKg) == TRUE, 0, 1)) %>%
  select(Date, Id, ActivityTracked, SleepTracked, WeightTracked) %>%
  group_by(Date) %>%
  summarize(
    n_activity = sum(ActivityTracked),
    n_sleep = sum(SleepTracked),
    n_weight = sum(WeightTracked)
  ) %>%
  pivot_longer(!Date, names_to = "feature", values_to = "count")

Now, we compute the median time spent sedentary, lightly active, fairly active, and very active for each day of the data collection period and prepare the data to be graphed.

# Create df of overall median daily time in each intensity category
intensity_ts <- daily_data %>%
  group_by(Date) %>%
  select(
    Date,
    VeryActiveMinutes,
    FairlyActiveMinutes,
    LightlyActiveMinutes,
    SedentaryMinutes
  ) %>%
  summarize(
    very_mdn = median(VeryActiveMinutes),
    fairly_mdn = median(FairlyActiveMinutes),
    lightly_mdn = median(LightlyActiveMinutes),
    sedentary_mdn = median(SedentaryMinutes)
  ) %>%
  pivot_longer(!Date, names_to = "intensity", values_to = "value")

Last, we compute the average time all participants spent within each activity intensity level across the entire data collection period and prepare the data for graphing.

# Create df of combined mean time spent within each intensity category
intensity_means <- daily_data %>%
  group_by(Id) %>%
  select(Id,
         VeryActiveMinutes,
         FairlyActiveMinutes,
         LightlyActiveMinutes,
         SedentaryMinutes) %>%
  summarize(across(where(is.numeric), mean),
            n = n()) %>%
  summarize(across(ends_with('Minutes'), ~ sum(n * .x)),
            total_n = sum(n)) %>%
  summarize(across(ends_with('Minutes'), ~ .x / total_n)) %>%
  pivot_longer(everything(),
               names_to = "intensity",
               values_to = "value") %>%
  mutate(intensity = factor(
    intensity,
    labels = c('Fairly Active', 'Lightly Active',
               'Sedentary', 'Very Active')
  )) %>%
  arrange(value)

Data Analysis and Visualization

# Universally define ggplot text size
textsize <- 12
# Create function to plot histograms for all desired variables
plot_hist <- function(colname, df) {
  # Compute median daily values for each participant
  medians <- df %>%
    group_by(Id) %>%
    summarize(mdn = median(.data[[colname]], na.rm = TRUE)) %>%
    drop_na(mdn)
  
  # Compute range of x axis data as distance of maximum value from 0
  xrange <- max(medians$mdn, na.rm = TRUE) - 0
  
  # Set x tic increments for daily steps
  if (xrange >= 15000) {
    xinc <- 4000
  }
  
  # Set x tic increments for daily calories
  else if (xrange < 15000 & xrange >= 3000) {
    xinc <- 500
  }
  
  # Set x tic increments for total daily active minutes and daily sedentary minutes
  else if (xrange < 3000 & xrange >= 350) {
    xinc <- 200
  }
  
  # Set x tic increments for daily lightly active minutes
  else if (xrange < 350 & xrange >= 100) {
    xinc <- 30
  }
  
  # Set x tic increments for daily fairly active minutes
  else if (xrange < 100 & xrange >= 40) {
    xinc <- 10
  }
  
  # Set x tic increments for daily distance
  else if (xrange < 40) {
    xinc <- 2
  }
  
  # Set minimum x value
  xmin <- 0
  
  # Round up to the nearest multiple of xinc and set as maximum x tick
  xmax <- ceiling(max(medians$mdn, na.rm = TRUE) / xinc) * xinc
  
  # Set the bin width so there are two bins per tic
  xbin <- xinc / 2
  
  # Center bar on middle of the bin
  center <- xbin / 2
  
  #Specify text size for labels and axes
  textsize <- 12
  
  # Create histogram with specified parameters and appropriate labels
  plot <- medians %>%
    ggplot(aes(x = mdn)) +
    geom_histogram(
      binwidth = xbin,
      center = center,
      fill = "deepskyblue4",
      color = "black",
      linewidth = .2,
    ) +
    scale_x_continuous(
      name = str_replace_all(
        colname,
        c(
          "Total" = "",
          "([[:upper:]])" = " \\1",
          "Calories" = "Calories Burned",
          "^" = "Median Daily"
        )
      ),
      limits = c(xmin, xmax),
      breaks = seq(xmin, xmax, xinc)
    ) +
    scale_y_continuous(limits = c(0, 20)) +
    theme_minimal() +
    theme(
      axis.text = element_text(size = textsize),
      axis.title.x = element_text(size = textsize),
      axis.title.y = element_blank()
    )
  
}
